\begin{abstract}
This paper presents a reconceptualized approach to mass generation in Conscious Point Physics (CPP), deriving Standard Model lepton and quark rest masses from quantized vibrational modes within 600-cell lattice cages. The restoring force is derived from SSV gradients, creating harmonic potentials. Frequencies are computed from cage geometry and Planck scales, with suppression from layer occupancy. We provide complete step-by-step derivations for the muon (tetrahedral cage) and charm quark (icosahedral), predicting masses ab initio and comparing to observed values (accepting initial discrepancies for refinement). Neutrino masses emerge as low-frequency modes. The framework resolves the hierarchy paradox through occupancy scaling, achieving order-of-magnitude agreement as an initial approximation without parameter tuning.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Paper 1 derived SSV gradient force laws and cage stability. This paper reconceptualizes mass as quantized vibrational energy of the central CP within its cage, derived from lattice geometry and Planck scales without experimental input. We define restoring forces, incorporate standard QM harmonic structure, and derive consistent scaling to address the hierarchy.

\section{Derivation of Restoring Force and Potential}

The restoring force for vibrations arises from SSV gradients between the central CP and shell CPs. For small displacements δr from equilibrium, the SSV potential approximates a harmonic form:

\begin{equation}
V(\delta r) = \frac{1}{2} k (\delta r)^2
\label{eq:harmonic_potential}
\end{equation}

where the spring constant k is derived from SSV gradients:

\begin{equation}
k = \frac{\text{SSV}_0}{d_0^2}
\label{eq:spring_constant}
\end{equation}

with SSV_0 = E_P / N_lattice ≈ 1.956 × 10^9 J / 120 ≈ 1.63 × 10^7 J (Planck energy divided by lattice vertices), and d_0 = l_P = √(ℏ G / c^3) ≈ 1.616 × 10^{-35} m (Planck length).

\section{Vibrational Frequencies}

The reduced mass μ_k for a cage of occupancy N_k is:

\begin{equation}
\mu_k = N_k \times m_P
\label{eq:reduced_mass}
\end{equation}

where m_P = √(ℏ c / G) ≈ 2.176 × 10^{-8} kg (Planck mass per CP equivalent).

The angular frequency ω_k is:

\begin{equation}
\omega_k = \sqrt{\frac{k}{\mu_k}} = \sqrt{\frac{\text{SSV}_0 / d_0^2}{N_k \times m_P}}
\label{eq:omega_k}
\end{equation}

\section{Quantum Mechanical Structure}

Using the standard harmonic oscillator:

\begin{equation}
E_n = \hbar \omega_k \left(n + \frac{1}{2}\right)
\label{eq:energy_levels}
\end{equation}

Rest mass energy is the zero-point:

\begin{equation}
m c^2 = \frac{1}{2} \hbar \omega_k
\label{eq:rest_mass}
\end{equation}

Generations correspond to higher n modes or k layers.

